data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you inspect the exception and pinpoints exactly which line threw:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName); // bonus: verify the right param
}
```

**Why:** `[ExpectedException]` is obsolete in modern MSTest — it can't verify exception details and will pass even if the *wrong* line throws. `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` scopes the check to the exact call and returns the exception for further assertions. Use `Assert.Throws<T>` instead if you also want to match derived exception types.
